'''Māori phonology''' is typical for [[Polynesian languages]], its [[Phonetics|phonetic]] inventory is one of the smallest in the world with considerable variation in realisation.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=15, 77}} The [[Māori language]] retains the [[Proto-Polynesian language|Proto-Polynesian]] syllable structure: ([[Consonant|C]])[[Vowel|V]](V(V)), with no closed [[syllable]]s.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=17}}{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=69}}{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=71}} The stress pattern is unpredictable unlike many other Polynesian languages.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=82}}
{{TOCleft}}
{{-}}

== Phonemes ==
The sound system of Māori is conservative; it is close to the system the Proto-[[Central Eastern Polynesian languages|Central Eastern Polynesian]] language had.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=62}} Most {{ill|Māori dialects|ru|диалекты маори}} have 10 consonant and 5 vowel [[phoneme]]s.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=62}} The most unstable phonemes are /f/ and /ŋ/.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=65}}

Despite the widely-held belief that the Māori phonetic system is simple and straightforward, in reality the realisation of Māori phonemes differs significantly; it depends on the speaker's age, the chosen [[Register (sociolinguistics)|register]] and other factors.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}}

The most frequent Māori phonemes are /a/ (18%), /i/ (11,3%), /t/ (9,8%).{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=68}} In an average text, vowels make up slightly more than 60 per cent of all the phonemes.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=68}} Several combinations are extremely rare: /fo/, /fu/; also /wo/ and /wu/ can only be found in [[loanword]]s.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=69}} The reason for the first two combinations to become rare is that *f + ''[[Roundedness|rounded]] vowel'' got merged with *s > /h/; the second pair was not attested in any reconstructions of the Proto-Polynesian language.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=70}}

=== Consonants ===
An unusual feature of Māori is the lack of [[sibilant]]s, the most frequently encountered type of [[Fricative consonant|fricative]] consonants, as well as the lack of {{IPAslink|j}} which is the most widespread [[semivowel]] phoneme in world languages.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=63}}

{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center"
|-
|+ Māori consonants
