! [[Semivowel]]
| {{IPAslink|w}}<ref name="w и v" group="NB">The phonemes /w/ and /u/ are close in articulation, but contrast in words like ''taua'' “you and me” and ''tawa'' “[[Beilschmiedia tawa|the tawa tree]]”.</ref>
|
|
|
|}

Unvoiced phonemes, /h/, and [[Fricative consonant|fricative]] [[allophone]]s of /t/ and /k/ are sporadically voiced in fast speech. Devoicing of sonorants has also been attested in the same environment.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}}

In loanwords, /h/ affects surrounding vowels by making them more [[Close vowel|close]].{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=64}}

The realisation of /t/ and /k/ can be [[Palatalization (sound change)|palatalised]] or [[Velarization|velarised]]; /t/ before /i/ and /u/ changes to an [[Affricate consonant|affricate]], {{IPAblink|t͡ʃ}}, especially if it occurs in the last syllable of the phrase.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}} Starting from the 19th century both /t/ and /k/ are increasingly aspirated. The article ''te'' can be pronounced as {{IPAblink|ð|ə}} in unstressed environment.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}} Sometimes /k/ is voiced to /ɣ/ in unstressed sylables.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}}

The [[place of articulation]] of /h/ is affected by the following vowel: ''hī'' “fish” is pronounced as {{IPAblink|ç|i|ː}}, but in ''hoa'' “friend” /h/ becomes [[Labialization|labialised]].

Most speakers pronounce /f/ as {{IPAblink|f}},{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}} but historically {{IPAblink|ɸ}} dominated; the realisations {{IPAblink|ʍ}} and {{IPAblink|h}} also occurred (see [[#Historical phonology]]).

The /r/ phoneme is most frequently realised as {{IPAblink|ɾ}}, sometimes it is pronounced as {{IPAblink|ɹ}} (in ''kōrero'' “speech”) and {{IPAblink|l}}; according to 19-century data, it was common for the dialects of the [[South Island]], but occurs everywhere.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=77}}

=== Vowels ===

{|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center"
|+ Māori vowels
!
! [[Front vowel|Front]]
! [[Central vowel|Central]]
! [[Back vowel|Back]]
|-
! [[Close vowel|Close]]
|{{IPAslink|i}}, {{IPAslink|iː}}
|
| {{IPAslink|u}}, {{IPAslink|uː}}<ref name="w и v" group="NB"/>
|-
![[Mid vowel|Mid]]
| {{IPAslink|e}}, {{IPAslink|eː}}
|
| {{IPAslink|o}}, {{IPAslink|oː}}
|-
![[Open vowel|Open]]
| colspan="3"| {{IPAslink|a}}, {{IPAslink|aː}}
|-
|}

The number of phonemes is small, so their realisation varies considerably.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=77}}

Phrase-final vowels can be reduced. This is especially true for short vowels, but it happens to long ones as well in fast speech.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=76}}

Like in [[New Zealand English]], the Māori phonemes /u/ and /uː/ are closer to [[central vowel]]s, that is, {{IPAblink|ʉ}}.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=80}}

For Māori monophtongs there are minimal pairs differentiated by [[vowel length]]:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=66}}
* kēkē “armpit” ~ keke “pie”;
* kākā “[[New Zealand kaka]]” ~ kaka “[[Plant stem|stem]]”;
* kōkō “[[Tui (bird)|tui]]” ~ koko “shovel”;
* kīkī “to speak” ~ kiki “to kick”;
* kūkū “[[New Zealand pigeon]]” ~ kuku “fear”.

Long vowels are pronounced for approximately twice as long as their short counterparts.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=79}}

Some linguists consider long vowels to be variants of the short ones, while others count them separately. The second approach is supported by the difference in quality between them: the long vowels are more centralised.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=67}}
* {{IPAslink|a}} is realised as {{IPAblink|ɐ}};
* /aː/ is realised as {{IPAblink|ɑː}}.

Beside [[monophthong]]s Māori has many [[diphthong]] vowel phonemes. Although any short vowel combinations are possible, researchers disagree on which combinations constitute diphthongs.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=69}} [[Formant]] frequency analysis distinguish /aĭ/, /aĕ/, /aŏ/, /aŭ/, /oŭ/ as diphthongs.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=79}}

== Phonotactics ==
Māori [[phonotactics]] is often described using a term '[[mora (linguistics)|mora]]' which in this context is a combination of a short vowel and a preceding consonant (if present). Long vowels and diphthongs are counted as two moras. With these units it is easier to set up boundaries for [[reduplication]], define [[allomorph]]s for some particles, and it also might be important to define the poetic meter of [[Māori poetry]].{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=71}}
* ''kaumātua'' “elder”{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=71}}:
** four [[syllable]]s: /kau.maa.tu.a/
** six moras: /ka.u.ma.a.tu.a/

For example, when the word  ''ako'' “to learn” is [[reduplication|reduplicated]], the resulted word ''akoako'' “give or take counsel” has the first syllable stressed, while the reduplication of ''oho'' “to wake up” -- ''ohooho'' “to be awake” -- often has the second syllable stressed. The reason is that /oa/ in the first example is a sequence of short vowels while /oo/ forms a single syllable peak.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=73}}

== Stress ==
Most Polynesian languages [[stress (linguistics)|stress]] the second to last mora of the word, but Māori stress is following many elaborate rules, which still remain not thoroughly understood.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=82}}. One of the rules requires assigning hierarchy to syllables, and if more than one syllable receives the highest rank, the first one gets stressed:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=82}}
# syllables with long vowels or geminate clusters;
# syllables with diphthongs;
# syllables with short vowels.

In addition to word stress, Māori has phrasal stress that falls on the second to last mora:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=83}}
* ''Ko te rangatíra, o tēnei márae'' “the [[rangatira]] of this [[marae]]”;
* ''Ko te maráe, o tēnei rángatira'' “the marae of this rangatira”.

This rule can also be applied to words that were formed by adding productive [[Voice (grammar)|passive]] and [[Nominalization|nominalisation]] suffixes:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=83}}
* ''káranga'' “call” > ''karánga-tia'' “be called”;
* ''rángatira'' “chief” > ''rangatíra-tanga'' “chiefdom”.

In reduplicated words, the first syllable of the repeated sequence has primary stress while the secondary stress falls on the first syllable of the second reduplication:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=83}}
* ''āníwanìwa'' “rainbow”.

The first syllable of the prefix ''whaka-'' “to cause something” is never stressed, but if it is added to a word starting with a vowel and forms a diphthong or a long vowel, the resulting syllable moves higher in the syllable hierarchy and might get stressed: ''whakap'''u'''ta'' “to emerge; to publish”, but ''whak'''aa'''ko'' “to teach”.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=84}}

Loanwords from English do not follow the rules at all.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=84}} Many researchers mention considerable variation in stress patterns.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=85}}

== Historical phonology ==
[[File:"Political Oceania" CIA World Factbook.jpg|thumb|300px|The map of Oceania]]
Reconstructions assume that [[Proto-Oceanic language]] had 23 consonant phonemes, and only 13 remained in [[Proto-Polynesian language]]: [[Voicelessness|unvoiced]] and voiced [[stop consonant]]s that contrasted in Proto-Oceanic merged, only two [[nasal consonant]]s remained, two more consonants disappeared completely, but at the same time Proto-Polynesian acquired [[vowel length]] distinction.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=15—16}} Māori retains all five Proto-Oceanic vowels.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=16}} From a [[Phonotactics|phonotactic]] standpoint, Proto-Polynesian lost consonant clusters and syllable-final consonants, although their [[Linguistic reconstruction|reflexes]] can still be found: the [[Voice (grammar)|passive]] form of the word ''inu'' “to drink” is ''inumia'', from *inum + ia.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=16}} Proto-Polynesian *[[Glottal stop|ʔ]] and *h disappeared in Māori, while *l and *r got merged into /r/ (the disappearance of /h/ and /l/-/t/ merger are typical innovations that can be found among the [[Nuclear Polynesian languages]], and the disappearance of /ʔ/ is typical for Proto-Central Eastern Polynesian languages.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=17}}

{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center;"
|-
| Proto-Polynesian || {{IPAslink|p}} || {{IPAslink|t}} || {{IPAslink|k}} || {{IPAslink|m}} || {{IPAslink|n}} || {{IPAslink|ŋ}} || {{IPAslink|w}} || {{IPAslink|f}} || {{IPAslink|l}} || {{IPAslink|r}} || {{IPAslink|s}} || {{IPAslink|ʔ}} || {{IPAslink|h}}
|-
| Māori{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=16}} || {{IPAslink|p}} || {{IPAslink|t}} || {{IPAslink|k}} || {{IPAslink|m}} || {{IPAslink|n}} || {{IPAslink|ŋ}} || {{IPAslink|w}} || {{IPAslink|f}}, {{IPAslink|h}}, {{IPAslink|w}} || colspan="2"| {{IPAslink|r}} || {{IPAslink|h}} || — || —
|-
|}

NB: /w/ is a very rare reflex of *f that is attested in five words as *faf became /wah/.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=17}}

Generally speaking, the Proto-Polynesian *f > /h/ before [[Labialization|labialised]] vowels, but is preserved as /f/ initially before non-labialised vowels.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=18}} Exceptions are likely reflecting that the merge of *f and *s took considerable time.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=18}} The /f/ ~ /h/ variation is also seen in dialects: *fea > /fea/ in western dialects of the [[North Island]], but /hea/ in eastern dialects.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=20}}

Many [[homophone]]s were formed due to the phonetic inventory shrinking: for example, the word ''tau'' “suitable” and the word ''tau'' “season” are stemming from Proto-Polynesian *tau and *taʔu, respectively. Another consequence of this change is the frequent occurrence of long vowels: Proto-Polynesian *kehe > ''kē''.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=17}}

Māori retains all the vowels Proto-Oceanic language had, but they underwent systematic changes:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=19}}
* Proto-Polynesian *u > /o/ in the second syllable (an innovation found in all Nuclear Polynesian panguages);
* word-initially, *a > /o/ (a [[Tahitic languages|Tahitic]] innovation);
* sometimes *a > /o/ (occurs in many Polynesian languages irregularly).

One of the many examples of irregular changes that happened in Māori is Proto-Polynesian *lima “hand” > Māori /riŋa/, although a related word *lima “five” turned into /rima/ in Māori; another one is a change from Proto-Eastern-Polynesian *aanuanua “rainbow” > ānuanua in [[Tahitian language|Tahitian]] while becoming āniwaniwa in Māori.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=20}}

Māori has many [[Doublet (linguistics)|doublets]] like /raŋo/ = /ŋaro/ (from Proto-Polynesian *laŋo) and /pouaru/ (North Island) = /poueru/ (South Island).{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=20}} Many of them occur due to [[Metathesis (linguistics)|metathesis]], or the rearranging of sounds. In Māori's case metathesis switches adjacent vowels, consonants or syllables; in addition to that there exists a rare type of metathesis that involves sound features instead of segments: in tenga ~ kenakena “Adam's apple” the consonants' [[place of articulation]] changes while retaining nasality; in inohi ~ unahi “scales” the subject of metathesis is the vowel labialisation, but not the [[vowel height]].{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=21}} Some [[morpheme]]s have [[allomorph]]s: for example, the [[prefix]] /ŋaːti/ changes to /ŋaːi/ if it is preceding a word that starts with /t/: /ŋaːti porou/, but /ŋaːi tahu/; the same can be observed for /motu/ (“island”): /''mou''tohoraː/, [[Moutohora Island]].{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=21}}

Māori has undergone several notable sound changes during the last 200 years, most likely under the influence of [[New Zealand English]] phonetic system: ''wh'' changed from [ɸ] to [f]; stop consonants /p/, /t/, /k/ acquired aspiration; /əʊ/ and /oʊ/ merged.{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=22—23}} Linguists studied several recordings of Māori and English speakers of different ages, that had been made in 1940s by the [[New Zealand Broadcasting Service]], and concluded that the change indeed took place. As an example, the results for ''wh'' can be found below:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=22—23}}
: {{IPAslink|ɸ}} 50 %
: {{IPAslink|ʍ}} 18 %
: {{IPAslink|f}} 13 %
: {{IPAslink|h}} 20 %<ref group="NB">''wh'' is realised as /h/ when it precedes /a/, usually in the unstressed prefix ''whaka-''.</ref>

The number of [[aspirated consonant|aspirated]] /p/, /t/, /k/ gradually increased, this change is also evident in recordings of speakers of different age:{{sfn|Harlow|2006|p=23}}
: recording from 1947, informant born in 1885: 6% aspirated
: recording from 2001, informant born in 1934: 49% aspirated
: recording from 2001, informant born in 1972: 88% aspirated

